lonialism, imperialism, capitalism, dependency, and relative international poverty. Brazil and the World System provides provocative insights not only about Brazil but also about the nature of colonialism in general and its relationship to the rise of capitalism in Europe. It should appeal to Latin Americanists of all disciplinary persuasions as well as to general readers curious about great patterns of change in history. Stuart Schwartz, director of the Center for Early Modern History at the University of Minnesota, says, “ . . . an excellent collection . . . North American scholarship will find these essays an eye-opener.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBrazil-Economic conditions. 0aBrazil-History-To 1822. 0aSlavery-Brazil-History. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aGraham, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovais, Fernando A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoares, Luís Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477304167423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477304167/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK